<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,704,1883]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,704,730]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Rosa" authorityName="Boustani &amp; Rosa" authorityYear="2022" box="[280,506,704,731]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mirae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[280,440,704,730]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Chrysis mirae</emphasis>
Rosa
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[517,609,705,731]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[517,609,705,731]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1806" box="[785,906,704,731]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis box="[785,906,704,731]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">C. elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. The female is characterized by straight genal carina, seen in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[629,717,740,767]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
); TFC not strongly elevated, partially faint; scapal basin widely polished medially (
<figureCitation box="[368,456,776,803]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
); tergum III apically arched, in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[961,1052,776,803]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
); in lateral view, post pit row area wide, its length more than 2–3 × times pit diameter (
<figureCitation box="[739,876,812,839]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Figs 5C, 5F</figureCitation>
); setae erected on tergum III dorsally. The male is recognizable by the shape of the black spots on sternum II (
<figureCitation box="[812,896,848,875]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1375,1399]" captionTargetBox="[153,1427,489,1351]" captionTargetId="figure-189@19.[151,1436,489,1351]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♂, paratype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Genital capsule. D) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. E) Habitus, lateral view. F) Metasoma, ventral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294424/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 6F</figureCitation>
); genital capsule, with elongate and curved apex of gonocoxa (
<figureCitation box="[305,397,884,910]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1375,1399]" captionTargetBox="[153,1427,489,1351]" captionTargetId="figure-189@19.[151,1436,489,1351]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♂, paratype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Genital capsule. D) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. E) Habitus, lateral view. F) Metasoma, ventral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294424/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Figs 6C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[409,459,885,911]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1561,1585]" captionTargetBox="[156,1428,1083,1527]" captionTargetId="figure-59@28.[151,1436,1075,1537]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 14. Genital capsules A) Chrysis verna Dahlbom, 1854. B) C. rasmonti sp. nov. C) C. mirae sp. nov. D) C. villosa sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294440" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294440/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">14C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
