<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,704,1883]" box="[199,951,1064,1091]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1064,1090]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[352,436,1064,1090]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Female</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[443,541,1064,1090]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[555,694,1064,1091]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Figs 5A–5F</figureCitation>
). Body length 9.3 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,704,1883]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis box="[199,260,1100,1126]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Head</emphasis>
. OOL 1.5 × MOD; POL 2.0 × MOD; MS 0.6 × MOD; relative length of P:F1:F2:F3 = 1.0:1.5:0.7:0.6. Punctures on brow between frontal carina and anterior ocellus dense, small (PD about 0.2 × MOD) and contiguous, without polished interspaces; punctures between ocellar triangle and eye scattered, interspaces polished, about 1.0 PD or wider; polished area lateral to posterior ocelli wide; TFC irregular, slightly raised medially, with two later undulations; lateral ending close to eye margin; genal carina straight, sharp, fully developed from temple to mandibular insertion (
<figureCitation box="[351,439,1280,1307]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
); scapal basin micropunctate laterally, widely polished medially, from uppermost margin to clypeal margin, forming subsquare, polished median area; malar spaces short (1.0 × MOD); subantennal space 1.0 × MOD; apex of clypeus dark brown, its apical profile triangular.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,704,1883]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis box="[199,319,1389,1414]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Mesosoma</emphasis>
. Medial pronotal line [= pronotal groove] slightly impressed, as long as 2/3rds length of pronotum; punctures on pronotum larger than those on vertex, interspaces polished with small dots; punctures on mesoscutum larger; punctures on median area of mesoscutum more spaced without small dots and extensively polished; notauli formed by deep, subrectangular foveae; parapsidal signum [= parapsidal line] deep and fully visible; punctures on mesoscutellum similar to those of mesoscutum, antero-medially more spaced; mesoscutellar-metanotal suture formed by deep punctures; punctures on metanotum deep, subcontiguous; posterior propodeal projections [= propodeal teeth] slightly divergent; faint episternal sulcus on mesopleuron, barely recognizable as slight depression.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,704,1883]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis box="[199,316,1641,1666]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Metasoma</emphasis>
. Punctures on terga I–III large and deep medially, interspaces narrow, with small dots; punctures smaller laterally, interspaces wider and polished; median longitudinal carina barely indicated on tergum II; tergum III without pre pit swelling; pits of pit row small, deep, partially confluent; lateral edge of tergum III with concavity before apical margin; apical margin (
<figureCitation box="[565,648,1748,1775]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 5F</figureCitation>
) slightly deflected, with narrow hyaline rim; slight undulations before lateral angles and apico-medially; post pit row area 2–3 × times pits diameter; black spots on sternum II large, as long as 3/5ths of segment length, close each other anteriorly, widely separated posteriorly; posterior margin slightly curved (
<figureCitation box="[243,329,1856,1883]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" startId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" targetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" targetPageId="18">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1196,1256]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1196,1220]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">FIGURE 5.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Rosa" authorityName="Boustani &amp; Rosa" authorityYear="2022" box="[280,481,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mirae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[280,422,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Chrysis mirae</emphasis>
Rosa
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[490,570,1196,1220]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[490,570,1196,1220]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1302,2013]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis box="[199,336,1302,1328]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Colouration</emphasis>
. Head and mesosoma metallic green; median area of mesoscutum dark blue to blackish on anterior half; metasoma golden dorsally; anterior declivity and apical margin of tergum I contrasting green; metasoma green ventrally; scape and pedicel green; flagellomeres dark brown; tegulae non-metallic brown; wings slightly infuscate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1302,2013]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis box="[199,296,1447,1472]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Vestiture</emphasis>
. Malar spaces, vertex and genae with scattered, whitish setae (1.0–1.5 × MOD); mesosoma laterally and legs, including trochanters, with extremely long (3.0–4.0 × MOD) erect and whitish setae (
<figureCitation box="[1215,1302,1482,1509]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
); metasoma laterally and ventrally with long (up to 4.0 × MOD), erect and whitish setae (
<figureCitation box="[1014,1099,1518,1545]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 5F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1302,2013]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis box="[199,257,1554,1580]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[272,407,1554,1580]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1375,1399]" captionTargetBox="[153,1427,489,1351]" captionTargetId="figure-189@19.[151,1436,489,1351]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♂, paratype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Genital capsule. D) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. E) Habitus, lateral view. F) Metasoma, ventral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294424/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figs 6A–6F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[419,467,1554,1580]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1561,1585]" captionTargetBox="[156,1428,1083,1527]" captionTargetId="figure-59@28.[151,1436,1075,1537]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 14. Genital capsules A) Chrysis verna Dahlbom, 1854. B) C. rasmonti sp. nov. C) C. mirae sp. nov. D) C. villosa sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294440" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294440/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">14C</figureCitation>
). Body length 9.0–9.5 mm. Similar to the female; sexual dimorphic characters are basitarsi distinctly lighter to whitish and reduced black spots on sternum II. Easily separable from the similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Rosa" authorityName="Boustani &amp; Rosa" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="villosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Chrysis villosa</emphasis>
Rosa
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[303,392,1626,1652]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[303,392,1626,1652]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by larger shape of black spots on sternum II (
<figureCitation box="[905,988,1626,1653]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1375,1399]" captionTargetBox="[153,1427,489,1351]" captionTargetId="figure-189@19.[151,1436,489,1351]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♂, paratype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Genital capsule. D) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. E) Habitus, lateral view. F) Metasoma, ventral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294424/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 6F</figureCitation>
) and genital capsule with elongate apex of gonocoxa (
<figureCitation box="[305,397,1662,1688]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1375,1399]" captionTargetBox="[153,1427,489,1351]" captionTargetId="figure-189@19.[151,1436,489,1351]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♂, paratype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Genital capsule. D) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. E) Habitus, lateral view. F) Metasoma, ventral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294424/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figs 6C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[409,466,1662,1688]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1561,1585]" captionTargetBox="[156,1428,1083,1527]" captionTargetId="figure-59@28.[151,1436,1075,1537]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 14. Genital capsules A) Chrysis verna Dahlbom, 1854. B) C. rasmonti sp. nov. C) C. mirae sp. nov. D) C. villosa sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294440" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294440/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">14 C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1302,2013]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1698,1724]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boustani &amp; Rosa" authorityYear="2022" box="[571,636,1699,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mirae">
<emphasis box="[571,636,1699,1724]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">mirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(feminine noun in genitive) is dedicated to Mira Boustani (Mons, 
<collectingCountry name="Belgium" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Belgium</collectingCountry>
), for her studies on the bees of 
<collectingCountry box="[559,657,1734,1760]" name="Lebanon" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Lebanon</collectingCountry>
and because she collected most of the recent cuckoo wasps examined in this study.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1302,2013]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,366,1806,1832]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Collecting site</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[381,467,1806,1832]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1169,1193]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,181,1145]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[152,1436,181,1145]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. A) View of the Horch Ehden Forest Reserve outskirts with sparsely wooded areas of Quercus sp., and Juniperus sp., and a dense herbaceous vegetation dominated by Medicago sp. B) View of the type locality of Chrysis mirae sp. nov. in the Supra-Mediterranean vegetation level with mainly Quercus sp., Pistachia sp., and Spartium junceum. The disturbed sandy-soil hosts many bee nesting sites. C) View of the type locality of Philoctetes acuminatus sp. nov. in the Oro-mediterranean.The vegetation is steppic with mainly Astragalus sp. thorny shrubs and Asphodeline taurica bulbous flowers. D) Flowers of Asphodeline taurica on which specimens of Philoctetes acuminatus sp. nov. were found." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257714/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus box="[535,583,1807,1833]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">type</typeStatus>
locality is in the Supra-Mediterranean vegetation level, with mainly 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1342,1436,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Quercus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[235,378,1842,1869]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Pistachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[235,341,1842,1868]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pistachia</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
woods, and 
<taxonomicName box="[516,719,1842,1868]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Spartium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="junceum">
<emphasis box="[516,719,1842,1868]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Spartium junceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the clearings and open areas. The site is a disturbed sandy-soil area with many solitary bee nesting sites and predominantly 
<taxonomicName box="[819,1056,1878,1904]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Echinops" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gaillardotii">
<emphasis box="[819,1056,1878,1904]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Echinops gaillardotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
flowering at the time of collection in June and July. The specimens were caught on flowers of both 
<taxonomicName box="[874,999,1915,1941]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" genus="Daucus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[874,960,1915,1940]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Daucus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1053,1211,1914,1940]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Echinops" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gaillardotii">
<emphasis box="[1053,1211,1914,1940]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">E. gaillardotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1302,2013]" lastBlockId="19.[151,1437,151,465]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1950,1976]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Rosa" authorityName="Boustani &amp; Rosa" authorityYear="2022" box="[323,548,1950,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mirae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[323,481,1950,1976]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Chrysis mirae</emphasis>
Rosa
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[560,650,1950,1976]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[560,650,1950,1976]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1806" box="[824,943,1950,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis box="[824,943,1950,1977]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">C. elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group and it is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Rosa" authorityName="Boustani &amp; Rosa" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="villosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">C. villosa</emphasis>
Rosa
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[301,390,1986,2012]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[301,390,1986,2012]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
The female is separated by: straight genal carina, seen in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[1175,1260,1986,2013]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
) (curved at mid gena in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boustani &amp; Rosa" authorityYear="2022" box="[240,347,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[240,347,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">C. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[362,463,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,777,1707]" captionTargetId="figure-265@25.[151,1436,777,1708]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 10. Chrysis villosa Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294430" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294430/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
)); subgena apparently more expanded, in lateral view, due to the different subgenal carina course; TFC not strongly elevated, partially faint (vs. strong and fully developed); scapal basin widely polished medially (
<figureCitation box="[266,354,222,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
) (vs. more densely punctate at sides, with a reduced impunctate area, triangularly shaped (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,777,1707]" captionTargetId="figure-265@25.[151,1436,777,1708]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 10. Chrysis villosa Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294430" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294430/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
)); metafemur less hairy (
<figureCitation box="[486,574,258,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
); tergum III apically arched, in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[1083,1171,258,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
) (vs. straight, with two blunt lateral corners (
<figureCitation box="[386,489,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,777,1707]" captionTargetId="figure-265@25.[151,1436,777,1708]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 10. Chrysis villosa Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294430" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294430/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
)); in lateral view, post pit row area wide, its length more than 2–3 × times pit diameter (
<figureCitation box="[159,291,330,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1196,1220]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-20@18.[151,1436,181,1172]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chrysis mirae Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6257734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6257734/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 5C, 5F</figureCitation>
) (vs. post pit row area narrow, as long as 1 pits diameter, or a little more (
<figureCitation box="[1102,1264,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,777,1707]" captionTargetId="figure-265@25.[151,1436,777,1708]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 10. Chrysis villosa Rosa, sp. nov., ♀, holotype. A) Habitus, dorsal view. B) Head, frontal view. C) Habitus, lateral view. D) Head, dorsal view. E) Habitus, ventral view. F) Metasoma, postero-lateral view. Scale bars 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6294430" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6294430/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 10C, 10F</figureCitation>
